03685nam a22006375i 9780814768594DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20032003nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147685947 a10.18574/97808147685942doi  a(DE-B1597)547370  a(OCoLC)782878029  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aML3531 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a782.42164900aNoise and Spirit :bThe Religious and Spiritual Sensibilities of Rap Music /cAnthony B. Pinn. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2003] 4cÂ©2003  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 African American Christian Rap: Facing "Truth" and Resisting It -- t2 A Jihad of Words -- t3 Rap, Reggae, and Religion -- t4 "Handlin'My Business" -- t5 Bringing Noise, Conjuring Spirit -- t6 Rap as Wrap and Rapture -- t7 The Spirit Is Willing and So Is the Flesh -- t8 The Rub -- t9 Rap, Religion, and New Realities -- tSelected Bibliography -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRap music is often seen as a Black secular response to pressing issues of our time. Yet, like spirituals, the blues, and gospel music, rap has deep connections to African American religious traditions.Noise and Spirit explores the diverse religious dimensions of rap stemming from Islam (including the Nation of Islam and Five Percent Nation), Rastafarianism, and Humanism, as well as Christianity. The volume examines rap's dialogue with religious traditions, from the ways in which Islamic rap music is used as a method of religious and political instruction to the uses of both the blues and Black women's rap for considering the distinction between God and the Devil.The first section explores rap's association with more easily recognizable religious traditions and communities such as Christianity and Islam. The next presents discussions of rap and important spiritual considerations, including on the topic of death. The final unit wrestles with ways to theologize about the relationship between the sacred and the profane in rap.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aRap (Music)xReligious aspects. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aPinn, Anthony B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814768594423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814768594.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK